definition: "The iron panel measures several interrelated values that together characterize the body's iron status. Serum iron measures the amount of iron circulating in the blood bound to transferrin — the primary iron transport protein. Total iron binding capacity (TIBC) measures the maximum amount of iron that transferrin can carry if fully saturated, reflecting the total available iron-binding capacity of the blood. Transferrin saturation (calculated as serum iron ÷ TIBC × 100) indicates what percentage of transferrin is currently carrying iron — the most sensitive measure of iron availability to tissues. Unsaturated iron binding capacity (UIBC) represents the remaining unfilled transferrin binding sites. Together, these values — combined with ferritin (iron storage) — provide a complete picture of iron metabolism: how much iron is circulating, how well the transport system is functioning, and how full the storage tanks are."
